{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532592/1921012301/0645.xml":{"full_text":"THRIFT vs. SPENDING\nTo The Public:\nAs I want you to read whatever\n?communications 1 may make to\nyou through the press now or at\nany other time and in whatever\nform they may appear, I wish to\nstate that you we not urged to read\nthis page but are warned against\ndoing so unless you have some\nspecially keen interest in the subjects\nunder discussion. This warning is\ngiven because I want you to feel that\nany message I may hereafter send\nyou is well worth the time required to\nread it.\nThere is a nation-wide Thrift\nMovement being initiated at this\ntime that has many firm supporters.\nThere is also opposition to ?this\nThrift Movement by those who be?\nlieve it is harmful to business and\nespecially at this time. Those advo?\ncating Thrift are so confident of\ngetting almost universal public sup?\nport that they desire to give the\nwidest publicity to everything that\ncan be said for ?and against Thrift.\nTfiey believe every \"knock,\" to\nthoughtful people, will prove to be a\n\"boost.\"\nThey desire to have these letters\npublished as a matter of record? While\nthese letters deal primarily with the\nquestion of whether Thrift or Spend?\ning is best for the country under\npresent conditions, they abo inci?\ndentally touch upon ?the Labor Ques?\ntion, the Banking Situation and ?the\nunemployment Problem. They may\npr?ve worm reading to those keenly\ninterested in these subjects and to stu?\ndents of Political Economy. If in\ndoubt whether this page is worth read?\ning 1 suggest you tear it out and lay it\naside to be read at your leisure if the\nsubject becomes one of further con?\ntroversy. You will undoubtedly hear\nmuch about Thrift, for further organi?\nzation work is going on now to carry it\nforward upon a still more comprehen?\nsive scale.\nYours cordially,\nHENRY L. DOHERTY\nA BUSINESS MESSAGE\nThe Buyers* Strike\nThrift vs. Spending\nThis advertisement was published in this paper\nTuesday, January 18, 1921.\nThis is addressed especially to the Retail Mer\ncbants,but we hop? everybody wiM read it This\nis National Thrift Week and hundreds of men\nand women are earnestly at work and want as\nmany more as possible to help them. Thrift\ndoes not mean hoarding, but means wise spend?\ning either for the ?comforts of life or insurance\nor bank reserves or investing. On Monday I re?\nceived the following letter:\nJanuary 17, 1921.\nMr. Henry L. Doherty,\n60 Wall Street,\nNew York City.\nDear Mr. Doherty:\nIt has been brought to our attention that\nsome of the retail merchants are not in\nsympathy with a Thrift Movement at this\ntime, believing it will be harmful to their\nbusiness. We are asking a number of our\nspeakers to assure the merchants that\nwe do not want to hurt their business\nbut want to help. Will you please do\nwhat you can to help U9 promptly cor?\nrect this matter.\nLet me suggest that you take this up in\nyour talk at the Brooklyn Central Branch\nof the Y. M. C. A. to-night, and perhaps\nyou would be willing to answer this mat?\nter through the press by interview or in\nyour own advertising space.\nVery truly yours,\n(sd) W. H. BAXLEY, Secretary,\nNew York City Thrift Committee.\nThi? appeals to me as a vastly important mat?\nter, for we want the support of these merchants,\nand as we are already in the campaign and as\nwe can reach so few people with our voices, I\nam glad to pay for the necessary space in the\ndairy paper? to say a little bit of the much we might\nsay at?? what w?? hope to accomplish.\nAll of as who are wholeheartedly supporting\nthe Thrift Movement believe it Is not only help?\nful to business but absolutely necessary for busi?\nness.\nAs a portion of Thrift Week is already gone\nwe cannot get together and harmonize our dif?\nferences of opinions; so the only thing left for us\nto do is to use space in the daily papers to present\nour views and invite those who dissent to present\ntheir views frankly and in a like manner.\nWe believe that Thrift and Investment is at\nall times helpful to business and that it is par?\nticularly needed just now. Our non-sympathizer?,\nwe understand, think Thrift and Investment is\ngenerally a good thing but that just, now it will\naccentuate the so-called Buyers' Strike.\nSome merchants seem to think that an Ameri?\ncan Federation of Retail Buyers has sprung up\novernight which in strength and determination is\ne^ual to the American Federation or Labor, and\nthat the first thing the new Federation did was\nto declare a Buyers' Strike.\nThere U no more of a \"Buyers' Strike\" among\nthe retail buyers than there is a Buyers' Strike\non the part of the retail merchants themselves.\nDon't you think that figures would show that the\npublic is buying more from the retail merchant\nthan the retail merchant is buying from the job?\nber and the manufacturer? How many retail\nmerchants do you think are willing to take the\nmoney their retail customer pays them and pas?*\nthe proper share of It right along to the jobber\nand to the fartory for more goods f\nHow many merchants do you think are al?\nready carrying lest than normal stocks??and how\nmany do you think of those who are carrying\nnormal or abnormal stocks would resist the temp?\ntation to reduce their, stocks far below normal\nif they ci-wld create enough retail buying to en?\nable them to do so?\nNow. we hare all seen some wonderfully clever\nsdvmisements teUing why the people should buy\nmerchandise liberally. I hope every merchant who\ni? not in sympathy with the National Thrift\nDrive will get these advertisements and read them\nover and make up bit mind how much of the\nadvice given to tne retail buyer he will accept\nfor himself and how much of this advice he thinki\nhi? fellow merchant will accept\nLet me remind you that our present troubles\nwere brought on largely by wild and extravagant\nbuying on the part of the public Retail mer?\nchants were encouraged to place abnormally large\norders to insure against depletion of stocks and\nrely on their banks to any them. This, with\nthe load the banks were already carrying, brought\na strain on our banking system which carried it\nto ita full elastic limit. Money thereafter had tr>\nbe rationell. The public in some cases bought\nuntil they had become weratocked and the retail\nmerchants in other cases bought until they hac\"\nbecome overstocked.\nThe retail customer does not buy in greater\nvolume, first, because the man out of employment\nis not apt to have the money or credit with which\nto buy and the man who ?9 still employed sees\nwidespread unemployment and wonders how secure\nhis employment is; second, because a large portion\nof the public think we are going to have still lower\nprices.\nNow, some of the retail merchants do not buy,\nfirst, because they fear that the business depression\nhas become so widespread that the future pur?\nchasing power of the American people has been\nseriously cjippled second, because they fear still\nlower prices; and third, because they are having\ndifficulty in raising the money necessary to pay\ntheir obligations when they come due.\nThere is nothing in the National Thrift move?\nment which opposes judicious or conservative\nbuying. There is no reason why the merchant\nshould not strive to stimulate buying, and there\nis no reason why he should not tell his customer\nthat it is his belief that prices have reached the\nbottom, if he really believes it himself.\nBut, Mr- Merchant, let's be fair again. We\nknow prices have been abnormally high. We all\nhoped they would come back to normal in a\ngradual and orderly manner?that they would\nevolute, not revolute; but when we reached the\nlimit of our banking credit, and the bankers had\nto call a halt, then, in many cases, factories, job?\nbers and retailers had to sell some of their goods\nfor whatever they would bring-?and here and\nthere some commodities had to be sold at less than\nthe pre-war cost of production.\nNow, what do you think ?9 the greatest threat\nof further demoralization of prices? I think the\ngreatest threat is to have further forced sales.\nDon't forget that many and in fact most of these\nforced sales were not due to lack of capital but\ndue to lack of cash. Don't forget, either, that\nthere are still many factories, jobbers and retailers\nwho are still under a great strain, and although\nthey have an abundance of capital yet they are\nfinding it difficult to find the cash to meet their\nobligations.\nThose of us who are supporting this National\nThrift movement believe that money applied to\nthese strained situations will do more to help the\nmercantile situation than a like amount of money\napplied to indiscriminate buying. Illustrating,\nperhaps by exaggeration, we feel that if the man\nwho has an appetite to smoke a one dollar im?\nported cigar wouuld content himself with a ten\ncent domestic cigar, and would say to the sound\nmerchant who is under a strain: \"Here is ninety\ncents that I will loan you to help prevent you\nfrom being compelled to make a forced sale of\nyour goods,\" we think that this would aid the\nentire business and mercantile situation more than\nif he had bought and smoked the one dollar cigar.\nNow, we know that ninety cents would not help\nvery much, and we know that this man, and the\nman like him, cannot deal direct with the mer?\nchant; but all of these people can deposit in some\nbank, which, in turn, will use it to help out these\nparticularly strained business situations and pre?\nvent forced selling.\nI know a great many of the men who are work?\ning wholeheartedly behind this National Thrift\nmovement. Many of them are merchants them?\nselves. None of them want to interfere with the\nbusiness of our merchants but to be helpful to\nthem. If we are wrong, you can tell the people\nwhy in the papers to-morrow.\nThe foregoing letter Is but little of what can\nbe said in favor of support of the National Thrift\nmovement but if what has already been said\nsounds reasonable then take a chance and get\nbehind the National Thrift Drive with your whole\nheart in it Give the public the assurance that\nthe business men of the country are fully cognizant\nof the situation, that they are not fearful about it\nand will not themselves \"hunt cover\" and that\nthey mean to correct the situation as rapidly as\ncircumstances will permit, and you will change the\nmind of the retail buyer overnight.\nConservative buying will again start up and the\nbuyer will pay what price he must whether he\nthinks it is the bottom price or not, and more will\nbe accomplished than by any attempt to break up\nthe so-called Buyers' Strike.\nThursday, if I am not called upon to make\nfurther reply along this line, I will tell yousome\nof the reasons why I am a decided optimist on\nthe business outlook provided the employers will\nget ?behind a Thrift and Investment Movement\nand try to show why wise investing is in truth\nwise spending and will help more than the ex?\npenditure which buys something which ?9 con?\nsumed.\nFaithfully your?,\nHENRY L. DOHERTY,\nSO Wall St, New York.\nTTi?s letter was released to the\npublicity columns of the press\nWednesday. January 19* 1921.\nNATIONAL PROSPERITY\nBUREAU\nlNC?SPOB,AT*ro\nExecutive Offices, Masonic Building,\nNew York City.\nJanuary 19, 1921.\nMr. Henry L. Doherty,\n60 WaU Street,\nNew York City.\nDear Sir:\nIt is not singular in these unsettled\nbusiness conditions that both the\n\"thrift'' campaign, of which you are\nan eminent exponent and spokesman,\nand the \"buy now\" movement, con?\nducted by the National Prosperity\nBureau, should arouse widespread\ninterest While there is much that\nis common ground in these efforts,\nthe impression persists in many quar?\nters that their purposes are antag\nonistic and that your own position in\nmany respects is self-contradictory.\nWe frankly agree with your ***ie\\vs\nthat economy and thrift, under nor?\nmal conditions, can and will do much\ngood with your contention that the\nretailer in many instances is himself\nengaged in a buyers' strike, and with\nyour premise that economic conditions\nhave been in a large measure the\nresult of extravagant buying. Like?\nwise, we agree with your conclusions\nthat many merchants are disinclined\nnow to replenish their stores because\nof your stated apprehensions.\nTo be equally frank, we find our?\nselves not entirely in accord with\nyour explanations of the causes of\nthese conditions and with your pro-\nposed remedies.\nThe a?xepted purpose or the\n'thrift\" campaign projected and car?\nried on at this time is to induce the\naverage man to get along with as\nlittle as he possibly can and to take\nthe balance of his earnings and place\nthese in a Savings Bank, or in an In?\nsurance Company to invest it, or,\nhimself, to invest it in recommended\ninvestment securities, thus enabling\nthose institutions to extend credit to\nclient?.\nWhat these clients, whether they be\nrailroads, manufacturing industries or\ntrading concerns, will do with mere\ncurrently and without an outlet for\ntheir <*ommodities, is rather obscure\nto us. All the money in the world, if\nthere is no demand for and consump?\ntion of the commodities which labor is\nengaged in producing, will not, we\nfear, relieve the demoralized situation.\nObviously, then, the thrift program\ncannot help us out of the situation.\nThe root of the entire evil, be the\ncause of it what it may, is the buy?\ners' strike, and the only remedy is a\nrevival of a public interest in pur?\nchasing.\nWhether the public is or is not\njustified in its present apathy is\nanother question. Some say that the\npublic strike is justified because the\nprices of commodities have not ap?\npreciably declined. On the other\nhand, the position is taken that the\nbuyers' strike is not justified because\nthe price of labor has not equally\nappreciably declined.\nThe public cannot on the one hand\ninsist on a maintenance of its pres?\nent wage-earning scale and on the\nother hand justify its refusal to pur?\nchase its needs. In any event, to\nlook for pre-war prices as a criterion\nfor prices to-day is manifestly un?\nsound, not only because of the rea?\nson just stated, but because of the\nadditional burden imposed upon all\nproduction by the tremendous war\nloans now being carried by business\nas a part of its general overhead.\nWc are not justifying high prices.\nOn the contrary, we consider it the\nfunction of all serious men to help\nmake prices more attractive to the\nconsumer in order to stimulate his\npurchasing activity.\nTo our way of thinking the only\nreal test of fair value is the price\nof any commodity when it reaches\nthe point at which it becomes attrac?\ntive enough for the public to purchase\nit. The ability and willingness of the\npublic to buy, and the tendency of\nbusiness men to enter and compete\nin new fields which promise large\nprofits, is a sufficient gauge, and at\nthe same time safety valve, for de?\ntermining fair prices at any particu?\nlar time.\nIt is because of this interpretation\nas to what constitutes a fair price of\ncommodities that we cannot agree\nwith your appraisal of the impor?\ntance which forced sates play in the\npresent demoralization of prices.\nAdmittedly, the thrift campaign is\ncalculated to prevent such forced\nsales. How ready are these financial\ninstitutions to prevent such forced\nsales into which financially embar?\nrassed clients are driven? Who will\nanswer this question on behalf of the\nbanks? Assuming that the banks or\nother financial institutions would be\nrash enough to loan money to clients\nin such a predicament, how is this\nclient?a manufacturer or dealer or\njobber?in a better position to ac?\ncelerate movement of his merchandise?\nTo us the danger of demoralization\nin prices is merely one of the effects\nof the greater cause which lies in\nthe buyers' refusal to buy, and, con?\ncurrently, in the weakening power of\nthe consumer to buy.\nv The buying power of the American\npeople was at its very highest some\nmonths ago, not only because all\nAmerican industry was then engaged\nand received the highest remunera?\ntion for its labor, but because labor,\nin spite of its spending orgy, had\nmanaged to accumulate money. The\nbuying power of the American peo?\nple has remained substantially unim?\npaired, except in spots where unem?\nployment and reduction in wages exist,\nboth of which were directly the result\nof the public's buying strike. Logical?\nly, business conditions will become\nmore aggravated by any increase of\nunemployment or further reduced\nwages; they will improve as industry\nresumes its normal functions, which\n?epend upon the free circulation of\nthe dollar.\nThese propositions are basic and\ncannot be waved aside by the op?\ntimistic prophesies that all that the\n\"public requires is assurance that the\nbusiness men are cognizant of the\nsituation''; that they are not fearful\nabout it and will not themselvei\n\"hunt cover.\"' Granted that the busi?\nness men realize the situation, and\ngranted that they are not fearful\nabout it, how are you going to dis?\npense over night with the menace\nof three million unemployed, with the\nlist growing, and with its power to\npa/ticipate in the market weakening?\nBy what miracle do you believe the\nmind of the retail buyer will be\nchanged over night in the mere be?\nlief that conditions will be corrected\nby business men \"cognizant of the\nsituation and not fearful about it\"?\nWe do not believe the panacea\nwhich you propose will reopen mills\nand replace three million men back\non to their jobs. That we realize to\nbe only capable of accomplishmen;\nwithin a reasonable time by an in?\ntensive campaign to educate the pub?\nlic to the urgency of keeping up the\nnormal buying of its needs and by\nteaching manufacturers, traders and\nretailers the necessity for attracting\nthe public into the martetplace.\nYours very truly,\nNational Prosperity Bureau, Ino.\nBy James Rosthal, Director.\n-_ ?^a^^s^s^saaa**a**^sm*w*msssm*ttSMmsit^s*\n,M| T: i ??z\nADVERTISEMENT_ADVERTISEMENT_ADVERTISEMENT\nsna-fl\"-?---^^\nThis letter is in response to the letter\nwhich appears to the left*\nJanuary 20th, 1921.\nNational Prosperity Bureau,\nMasonic Building,\nNew YoAc City.\nGentlemen:\nI received your letter of the 19th at 3:45\nP. M. while presiding over a regular monthly\nmeeting of the Board of Directors of Cities\nService Company, and owing to this and to sev?\neral other rapidly succeeding engagements until\nquite late in the evening I was unable to reply\nuntil to-day.\nFirst let me express my appreciation of the\ntone of your letter. While I cannot agree with\nyour position, nevertheless I give you credit for\nbeing as sineere in your views as I know*I am\nin mine.\nIf the \"impression persists that\nyour own [my] position is self-contradictory\"\nI want to correct it, if possible. I always try\nto think straight and then try to speak or write\nmy thoughts plainly. If I am wrong in any\nway I will be glad to be set right, and if I have\nadvocated a wrong poliqy I will without hesi?\ntancy publicly endeavor to make amends. These\nare times when our difficulties entitle the public\nto earnest discussion to harmonize differences\nof opinion rather than argue for the sake of\njustifying a selfish position.\nI have carefully read your letter with an\nearnest endeavor to preserve an open mind, and\nit is only fair to you to say that it has not\nchanged my opinion in the least.\nYou admit in the second paragraph of your\nletter that the present \"economic conditions\nhave been in a large measure the result of ex?\ntravagant buying.\" Now, if you had a patient\nwho was suffering from over-eating, you would\nnot resort to Jbrced-feedir g when his stomach\nturned against fdod simply because he had\nspeeded up his favorite restaurant to a certain\nvolume of business and that therefore this vol?\nume of business had to be maintained. Or, if\nyou had a patient suffering from over-drinking,\nyou would not urge him to drink more just\nbecause his wine merchant had become over?\nstocked, even though this stock had been\ncontracted for- ba'sed upon his former rate of\npatronage.\nYou say, \"The l-oot of the entire evil\nIs the buyers' strike.\" Surely you\ndo not mean that the buyers' strike is what has\nproduced our present situation. It is far from\na \"root.\" It is a natural reaction from the\n\"spending orgy\" which prevailed, and which\nyou speak about in the thirteenth paragraph\nof your letter. Before the \"spending orgy\" had\nspent itself we-had reached the point in our\nfinancial strain which in the judgment of our\nbankers required them to call a halt and to\nplace the business world on rationed loans.\nI cannot accept, and do not necessarily dis?\npute, the statement you made in the fourth par?\nagraph of your letter, My idea of Thrift is,\nWork and Earn?Don't Waste. Save part of\nwhat you earn and deposit or invest it where it\nis safe and where it will go you the most good.\nThere are hundreds of men who have abun?\ndant capital who are applicants for the loan of\ncash from their banks, but the banks are unable\nto loan them as freely as they need the money\nor as these banks would like to do; but these\nbanks, and especially the commercial banks, can\nbe depended upon to loan this money wherever\nit is safe and where it is most needed rather\nthan to l?\\an it purely for their own selfish in?\nterest. Inability of many manufacturing con?\ncerns to raise cash by the pledge of capital is\nwhat has caused the vast army of unemployed\nGive them a chance to get cash for the^pledge\nof capital and the*?/ will resume operations, giv?\ning employment to the unemployed, thus re?\nestablishing the purchasing power of the public\nand enabling themselves to convert capital into\ncash with which to repay these loans.\nPeople will buy if they have money to buy\nwith?and the world problem has never been to\nstimulate the need and desire for consumption,\nbut to produce in sufficient abundance what is\nneeded for consumption. What brought us to\nour present situation was the tendency to con?\nsume until wo had eaten our seed corn. So I\ncannot concur in your statement that \"Obvious?\nly then the thrift program cannot help us out\nof the situation.\"\nWe who are advocating Thrift as a cure for\nour troubles cannot undertake to have either\nlabor or the banks conduct themselves to your\nliking, but we will gladly join with you to in?\nduce the banks or labor to do that which is\nbest for our country as a whole, believing in this\npresent situation that each and every interest\nwill prosper more with a thoroughly sound\ncondition of the country throughout than by\nhaving some selfish advantage over others\nthrough what may prove a period of great busi?\nness depression.\nYou refer to Labor in a way which questions\nwhether its attitude is constructive in the\npresent situation, and I think you may well do\nso. But do not forget that we are apt to see\nthe faults of others more readily than we see\ntheir virtues. The world's progress has largely\nbeen brought about by the creation and intro?\nduction of labor-saving machinery. We cannot\ndeny that the introduction of every epoch\nmaking piece of labor-saving machinery seri?\nously inconvenienced, and sometimes punished,\nlarge groups of wage-earners, and yet we know\nthat Labor could never have enjoyed its present\ncomfort of living and short labor hours that are\nnow possible if it had not b??en for the introduc?\ntion of this labor-saving machinery. Every\nother country has been compelled to fight the\nfalse but plausible doctrines of ???*?onomy that\nhave been advanced to prevent the introduction\nof labor-saving machinery to a greater extent\nthan have we. Our American Labor has been\nvastly more constructive than many men give\nthem credit for. And while not defending Or?\nganized Labor, J could cite other examples of\nthe virtue of American Labor if called upon to\ndo so. I mention this one example, and state\nthat the position of the merchants who oppose\nthe Thrift and Investment Movement is based\non equally false economic premises, and, while\nhighly plausible, is still not so plausible or justi?\nfiable as the opposition of Labor to the intro?\nduction of labor-saving machinery.\nSurely the merchants, unconsciously prompt?\ned by selfish interests, do not want to fall into\nthe error of supporting a false economic doctrine\nthat lacks even the plausibility or justification\nof things which even Organized Labor has not\nfallen error to. Here is a statement, and I\ndon't see how it can be successfully contradicted\nby any amount of argument, viz. The more we\ncreate and the less we consume, the greater\nwill be our accumulation of wealth. All the\nlabor for many generations to come can find\nabundant employment along the lines which\ncreate permanent property in the true sense,\nand the need and desire for consumption do\nnot have to be stimulated to provide employ?\nment.\nI can neither concur in, nor do I here take\nexception, to the definition of a \"fair price\" as\ngiven in the tenth paragraph of your letter.\nMy own way of stating the njatural laws which\nfix prices is by saying?Except \"under emergency\nconditions natural laws fix as a minimum price\nthe cost of production when it reaches the con?\nsumer in final form, and its maximum price is its\nvalue to the consumer regardless of its price of\nproduction; but, generally speaking, a \"fair\nprice\" is that which properly, but not unwar\nrantedly, rewards those who produce and dis?\ntribute and gives sufficient reward to attract\nboth capital and labor.\nForced sales, however, entirely disregard\nnatural laws as to cost of production, and moral\nlaws as to fair prices, and forced purchases do\nlikewise in the opposite direction. The mar\nwithout water, or sufficient water, stranded or\nthe desert, will pay' any price he may have tc\nfor water?and that brings me to this point,\nviz.: that I fear that many of our retail mer?\nchants failed to console themselves with an?\nother very natural application of natural laws\nWhen prices were ascending they found them\nselves able to sell their goods at more than i\nfair margin above their cost, and yet they j\\o\nonly failed to set aside a contingent fund 01\ntheir books, or a contingent thought in thei:\nminds that when prices would again deseen?\nto normal they would find themselves victims o\nthe reaction of an economic law and compeli?\njit\nto accept some losses, just as they had takei\ntheir profits.\nNow, just to save you the trouble of callin\nmy attention to the fact that the Treasury's ru\n:ngs did not adequately provide for this of\nsetting of profits against inevitable losses, I wi\nadmit it. On the other hand, those of us wr\nadvocate Thrift do not attempt to defend tl\npresent Revenue Law or the Treasury's rulin?\n?and we think the law was a most unthrifl\none.\nReferring to your quotation of my staternen\nin the fourteenth paragraph of your letter,\nwish to say that I had no intention of setting i\na mere figment in the minds of the people th\nwas without substance. I stand ready to do r\nshare toward any movement which will arrt\nfurther demoralization?but it would be t\niong a matter to suggest and discuss plans he\nby letter. The financial trade conditions ha\nbeen turned many times by co-operation a\ndetermination, but I am unable at this mome\nto refer to any concrete example in the mere*\ntile trades; but any of the frecruent examp]\nin the financial world are equally applicable\nthe mercantile world. Perhaps the most 01\nstanding one in the financial world, and fr?\nwhich you might borrow an example, was t\nway the Baring Brothers Crisis was met a\nsolved in 1890 by the. London banking hous\nled by officials of the Bank of England. I\ngret that I cannot at this moment cite you\nsome book which will detail this to you, but v\nendeavor to make a search of my library t\nevening and tell you definitely where you\nread up about it.\nNow, I hope I have convinced you that\ndo not want to doctor this patient who is s\nfering from over-eating by further fore\nfeeding. He will soon buy and eat more if\ndo not resort to forced-feeding while Ire is\nI also hope this letter will convert you to\nThrift Plan. If it does, get in quick and\nyour whole heart, for it means, in my opin\nthe speediest cure for our ailments. K\never, whether I have or not, let's not be tl\nskinned, and let's try and set an example wh\nby all of the differences of opinion regare\nour big national questions can be settled\nearnest discussion rather than by long con\nversies, whether it is a financial, an indust:\ns mercantile or a labor problem.\nYours cordially,\n(Signed) HENRY L, DOHERT1","height":"25203","width":"19911"}}
